body:
I read through the code and the culprit seems to be this fragment of `HttpObjectDecoder`:
```
    if (!isDecodingRequest()) {
            HttpResponse res = (HttpResponse) message;
            if (res != null && res.status().code() == 101) {
                currentState = State.UPGRADED;
                return;
            }
        }
```

The problem is that it assumes that every Upgrade will cause replacement of `HttpClientCodec` with something else (e.g. HTTP 2 handler). Unfortunately with TLS this is not the case, because the protocol switch happens at a different layer. 

Maybe it would be ok if `HttpClientCodec` entered UPGRADED state only if `Upgrade` header did not contain `HTTP/1.x` string?
